  "teaching": {
    "purpose": "Show a two-suited hand (5-5 or better) when an opponent opens a suit, enabling partner to choose the best fit at a competitive level",
    "whenToUse": "After opponent opens 1C/1D/1H/1S: cue-bid their suit to show a two-suited hand, or bid 2NT to show both minors. Over a minor opening, the cue bid shows both majors. Over a major, it shows the other major plus an unspecified minor.",
    "whenNotToUse": [
      "With only 5-4 shape — need 5-5 or better",
      "With a strong balanced hand — don't confuse with a Western Cue Bid",
      "Against 1NT — use DONT instead"
    ],
    "tradeoff": "Michaels sacrifices the natural/strong meaning of the cue bid and 2NT in exchange for immediately showing a two-suited competitive hand",
    "principle": "Showing two suits simultaneously lets partner judge fit quickly. The vulnerability-gated HCP range (looser NV, tighter Vul) reflects the risk/reward of competing.",
    "roles": "Overcaller describes shape; advancer evaluates fit and chooses the best strain and level"
